-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: KenolKobil, Oando of Nigeria Active
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2012-06-28T16:03:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-28/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenolkobil-united-bank-for-africa.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index fell 0.2 percent to 21,542.24 by the close in Lagos,
paring its gain in the second quarter to 4.3 percent, according
to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  declined for the first day in
three, falling 0.3 percent to 67.39 in Nairobi. Mauritius’s
 SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  advanced for the first time in three days, rising
less than 0.1 percent to 1,776.58 in Port Louis. The
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  declined for a sixth day, its longest
losing streak in more than ten months, dropping 1.5 percent to
876.91 in Windhoek.  The following shares are active in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC)  , a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in nine African nations, fell the most in more than
two years, sliding 8.9 percent to 14.30 shillings. The Standard
newspaper reported the country’s Industrial Court blocked a
potential takeover by Puma Energy BV.  Oando Plc (OANDO)  , an energy company, slid to its lowest
in more than nine years, dropping 2.3 percent to 12.80 naira.
Oil fell for the first time in three days, extending losses in
the worst quarter for Nigeria’s biggest export since 2008.  To contact the reporter on this story:
